The Story of AI (From Rule-Based Systems to ChatGPT)

Stage 1: Rule-Based AI (1950s–1980s)
Why did AI start?
People wanted computers to behave intelligently.
For example, they wanted a computer to answer questions like:
"Is this email spam?"
"Should a patient take this medicine?"
"Can a chess program make the next move?"
At that time, computers couldn't learn. They only followed instructions.
So programmers wrote rules.

Example:

IF email contains "Congratulations"
AND email contains "Prize"
THEN Spam

IF temperature > 38°C
THEN Fever

Problem

This worked for simple tasks, but imagine Gmail receiving millions of emails.

People don't always write:

Congratulations! You won a prize!

They might write:

Claim your reward
Free gift waiting
You've been selected
Win cash today

The programmer would have to keep adding new rules forever.

Rule-based AI became difficult to maintain and couldn't handle new situations it had never seen before.


Stage 2: Machine Learning (1990s–2010)

Researchers asked a different question.

Instead of writing thousands of rules...

Can the computer learn the rules from data?

Example:

Give the computer:

Email	Spam?
Win money	Yes
Meeting at 3 PM	No
Claim your prize	Yes
Project update	No

Instead of writing:

IF contains prize THEN spam

the algorithm studies many examples and discovers patterns by itself.

This was the birth of Machine Learning.

Problem solved
No need to manually write every rule.
The computer could improve by learning from more examples.
New problem

The programmer still had to tell the computer which features to look at.

For spam detection, they manually created features like:

Number of links
Number of capital letters
Contains "free"
Contains "offer"

This process is called feature engineering.

If the chosen features were poor, the model performed poorly.

Stage 3: Deep Learning (2012 onwards)

Researchers wondered:

Can the computer automatically learn the important features too?

Instead of manually creating features, they built neural networks.

Neural networks learn patterns directly from raw data.

Example:

Image classification.

Machine Learning:

The programmer extracts:

Eye shape
Ear size
Tail length

Deep Learning:

Just provide thousands of cat and dog images.

The neural network learns by itself:

Edges
Eyes
Whiskers
Fur
Face

No manual feature engineering.

Problem solved
Much better accuracy.
Works well for images, speech, and language.
Learns complex patterns automatically.
New problem

Text is harder than images.

Language depends on context.

Example:

"The bank is near the river."

vs.

"I deposited money in the bank."

The word bank has different meanings.

Older deep learning models struggled with long sentences.


Stage 4: RNN and LSTM (Early Deep Learning for Text)

Researchers created models specifically for sequences of words.

They introduced:

RNN (Recurrent Neural Network)
LSTM (Long Short-Term Memory)

These models processed one word at a time and tried to remember previous words.

For example:

The cat is sleeping.

When reading "sleeping", the model tries to remember "cat".

Problem

If the sentence becomes very long:

The cat that my friend adopted last year from a shelter is sleeping.

The model may forget earlier words.

This is known as the long-term dependency problem.

Stage 5: Transformers (2017)

Researchers asked:

Why read words one by one? Why not look at the whole sentence at once?

They introduced the Transformer architecture.

Its key innovation is the Attention Mechanism.

Instead of remembering everything sequentially, it directly focuses on the most relevant words.

Example:

The cat that my friend adopted last year is sleeping.

When predicting "sleeping", the model pays more attention to "cat" than to "last year".

Problem solved
Understands long sentences much better.
Faster to train because words can be processed in parallel.
Captures context more effectively.

This was a huge breakthrough.


Stage 6: Large Language Models (LLMs)

Researchers thought:

What if we train a transformer on almost the entire internet?

They collected massive datasets:

Books
Articles
Wikipedia
Websites
Research papers

The transformer learned:

Grammar
Facts
Reasoning patterns
Programming
Writing styles

These huge transformer models became Large Language Models (LLMs).

Examples:

GPT
Llama
Claude
Gemini

Notice:

An LLM is not a new type of AI.

It is a very large transformer-based deep learning model.


Stage 7: Generative AI

People then realized:

These LLMs don't just understand text—they can generate it.

They can:

Write emails
Answer questions
Translate languages
Generate code
Summarize documents

This is called Generative AI because it generates new content.

Stage 8: AI-Powered Applications

Now developers use pretrained LLMs to build real applications.

For example, an HR chatbot.

The developer builds:

User interface
Backend (FastAPI)
Authentication
Database
Chat history
Logging
RAG to retrieve company documents

The LLM provides the language intelligence.

The application combines everything into a usable product.

Examples:

ChatGPT
Claude
Microsoft Copilot
Customer support bots
HR assistants
Medical assistants


