NLP is the "problem" we want to solve (understanding human language).

Rule-Based AI, Machine Learning, Deep Learning, Transformers, and LLMs are different "approaches" that humans developed over time to solve NLP problems more effectively.






➡️ Deep Learning (Neural Networks)

The neural network automatically learned useful features.

Step 3: Deep Learning
Problem solved

No need for humans to manually design features.

Example:

For image recognition:

Instead of telling the computer:

Look for ears
Look for whiskers
Look for a tail

The neural network learned those patterns itself.

New limitation

Language is much harder than images.

Words depend on context.

Example:

I went to the bank.

Does "bank" mean:

A financial institution?
The side of a river?

The meaning depends on the surrounding words.

New method that solved it

➡️ RNN (Recurrent Neural Network)

RNNs process words in sequence and remember previous words.

Step 4: RNN
Problem solved

The model remembers earlier words.

Example:

I love AI.

When reading "AI", it remembers "I love".

New limitation

For long sentences, RNNs forget earlier information.

Example:

The student who moved from Chennai last year and joined the university recently won the award.

By the time it reaches "award", it may have forgotten "student".

This is called the long-term dependency problem.

New method that solved it

➡️ LSTM (Long Short-Term Memory)

LSTMs remember information for longer.

Step 5: LSTM
Problem solved

Better memory for long sequences.

New limitation

Still processes one word after another.

That makes training slow and makes it hard to capture very long relationships efficiently.

New method that solved it

➡️ Transformer

Step 6: Transformer
Problem solved

Instead of reading one word at a time, the model looks at the whole sentence and uses attention to focus on the most relevant words.

Example:

The cat that my friend adopted last year is sleeping.

When processing "sleeping", the model pays attention to "cat".

New limitation

Transformers worked well, but researchers wondered:

What if we train a transformer on massive amounts of text?

New method that solved it

➡️ Large Language Models (LLMs)

Step 7: Large Language Models (LLMs)
Problem solved

Train one huge transformer on books, websites, code, and articles.

Now one model can:

Answer questions
Translate languages
Write code
Summarize text
Explain concepts

instead of building a separate model for each task.

New limitation

LLMs don't automatically know your company's private documents or the latest information after their training cutoff.

New method that helped solve it

➡️ RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation)

RAG retrieves relevant external information and gives it to the LLM before it answers.

Step 8: AI Applications

Now developers build applications around LLMs.

Examples:

ChatGPT
HR Assistants
Customer Support Bots
Medical Assistants
Coding Assistants

The developer builds:

UI
Backend
Database
Authentication
Logging
RAG
APIs

The LLM acts as the language brain.

